ğŸ“Œ 2. Forking the Repository

If you are external to the main repo, you must fork.

Go to the GitHub repository

Click Fork (top right)

GitHub creates a copy under your username

You will push changes to your fork â†’ then open Pull Requests

ğŸ“Œ 3. Cloning and Setup
Clone the Main or Forked Repo
git clone https://github.com/<your-username>/Meal-Planning-using-GA.git
cd Meal-Planning-using-GA

Add the Original Repository as Upstream (important)
git remote add upstream https://github.com/dontbelikesdb/Meal-Planning-using-GA.git

Check remotes
git remote -v


Should show:

origin    <your fork>
upstream  <main/original>

ğŸ“Œ 4. Branch Management
Branch Naming Convention

Use clear prefixes:

Purpose	Prefix	Example
Feature	feat/	feat/add-login-page
Fix	fix/	fix/recipe-api-bug
Docs	docs/	docs/update-readme
Refactor	refactor/	refactor/ga-module
Create a Branch
git checkout -b feat/new-feature

Switch Branch
git checkout main

Delete a Branch
git branch -d feat/new-feature

ğŸ“Œ 5. Daily Workflow (Important!)

Every day before you start working:

1. Switch to main
git checkout main

2. Pull latest changes from main repo
git pull upstream main

3. Update your fork
git push origin main

4. Create a new branch for the dayâ€™s work
git checkout -b feat/todays-task


Then continue coding.

ğŸ“Œ 6. Pull Request Process
Step-by-step

Commit your code on your feature branch

Push to your fork:

git push origin feat/todays-task


Go to GitHub â†’ your fork

Click Compare & Pull Request

Fill PR template:

Summary of changes

Screenshot (if UI)

Linked issue number

Steps to test

Submit PR

Wait for code review

Apply requested changes

Reviewer approves â†’ Merge

ğŸ“Œ 7. Code Review Guidelines
As a Reviewer:

âœ” Check code readability
âœ” Check if feature follows architecture
âœ” Confirm there are no security issues
âœ” Look for duplication
âœ” Run code locally if needed
âœ” Suggest improvements, not insults
âœ” Approve only when:

tests pass

CI passes

code quality is good

As an Author:

âœ” Be open to feedback
âœ” Commit updates requested in review
âœ” Never argueâ€”explain calmly if needed

ğŸ“Œ 8. Conflict Resolution
When Git Shows a Merge Conflict:

Open the conflicted file

Find markers:

<<<<<<< HEAD
Your changes
=======
Incoming changes
>>>>>>> branch-name


Manually edit & keep correct version

Remove markers

Add resolved file:

git add filename


Continue merge:

git commit

Avoid conflicts by:

pulling latest code daily

not committing large chunks at once

using meaningful branches

ğŸ“Œ 9. Essential Git Commands
Check status
git status

Stage changes
git add .

Commit
git commit -m "Meaningful commit message"

Push branch
git push origin branch-name

Fetch updates (no merge)
git fetch upstream

Merge updates
git merge upstream/main

Stash changes temporarily
git stash

Apply stashed changes
git stash pop

ğŸ“Œ 10. Best Practices
âœ” Commit small, frequent updates
âœ” Use meaningful commit messages
âœ” One PR = One Feature
âœ” Never push directly to main
âœ” Always create a feature branch
âœ” Keep your fork updated every day
âœ” Write clear documentation
âœ” Use .env.example to show required variables
ğŸ“Œ 11. Troubleshooting
â—â€œPermission deniedâ€ when pushing

You are pushing to the original repo.
Fix:

git push origin branch-name

â—"Your branch is behind 'upstream/main'"

Fix:

